Deploying on Beachhead — include a beachhead.json in the repo root specifying public_service (the service name that handles HTTP, e.g. frontend) and public_port (e.g. 80). In docker-compose.yml: no version: key; use expose: not ports: for all services (Beachhead's nginx-proxy handles routing); do NOT set container_name on any service (Beachhead sets unique names per deployment via its override — a hardcoded name will conflict and crash the deploy); ALL services must be on an explicitly named internal network — add `networks: [internal]` to every service and a top-level `networks: {internal:}` entry, otherwise Beachhead's override replaces the frontend's implicit default network and cuts it off from the backend; postgres healthcheck must have start_period: 30s; database volume must use a fixed name: (e.g. name: myapp-postgres) — without it every redeploy creates a fresh volume and wipes the database; frontend nginx must proxy to backend by Docker service name (not localhost). IMPORTANT: nginx resolves upstream hostnames at config load time — if the backend container isn't ready yet, nginx will crash with "host not found in upstream". Fix this by using Docker's embedded DNS resolver and a variable for proxy_pass so resolution happens at request time, not startup. In nginx.conf use: `resolver 127.0.0.11 valid=30s ipv6=off; set $backend_upstream http://backend:3001; proxy_pass $backend_upstream;` instead of a bare `proxy_pass http://backend:3001;`. The `ipv6=off` is required — without it Docker's embedded DNS returns SERVFAIL on AAAA (IPv6) lookups, causing "backend could not be resolved (2: Server failure)" errors at request time even though the startup crash is fixed. Set DB_PASSWORD and any vars shared between services as global env vars in the Beachhead dashboard (no Target Service) so they're written to .env for Docker Compose variable substitution. Use npm install not npm ci in Dockerfiles. STATEFUL SERVICES: If your app includes a stateful service (e.g. a database) that must NOT be recreated on each blue/green deploy, declare it in beachhead.json as `"stateful_services": ["postgres"]`. Beachhead will run those services under a fixed Docker Compose project name (`{app-slug}-stateful`) that persists across all deploys, so the container is never stopped or recreated during a swap — only started if not already running. All other services (frontend, backend, etc.) continue to be swapped blue/green as normal. Apps without `stateful_services` are unaffected. The stateful service must still be defined in docker-compose.yml with all its config (image, volumes, healthcheck, etc.) — Beachhead reads the config from the current deploy's compose file, it just runs it under the stable project name. Named volumes on stateful services work as normal since Beachhead pre-creates named volumes as external before any compose up call.